Array functions.

Array columns are first-class citizens in Spark, and the function library has both builders that create arrays and flatteners that break them apart.

On the building side, the array function assembles an array from several columns or literals. Array-contains asks whether a value is present and returns a boolean. Size gives you the element count. And there is a full set of array set operations — distinct, union, intersect, and except — that work element-wise.

On the flattening side, the most important function is explode. Explode turns one row with an array of n elements into n separate rows, one per element. It is how you go from a compact array representation to a long, one-row-per-item shape ready for grouping.

There is a subtlety with nulls that the exam loves. Plain explode drops rows whose array is null entirely — they vanish from the output. If you need those rows to survive, use explode-outer, which keeps a null-array row as a single row with a null value. The related pos-explode also hands you the index alongside each element.

And flatten collapses an array of arrays down by exactly one level — useful, but remember it is one level only, not a deep flatten.
